# useState Example ğŸ”¢

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';

function Counter() {
  // count starts at 0
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>You clicked {count} times</p>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Click me
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

# Functional Updates ğŸ”„

If the new state depends on the old state, pass a function to the setter.

```jsx
// Risky (if rapid updates happen)
setCount(count + 1);

// Safe (guarantees latest value)
setCount(prevCount => prevCount + 1);
```

# Objects in State ğŸ“¦

`useState` does NOT merge objects automatically (unlike `this.setState` in classes).

```jsx
const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: "John", age: 30 });

// To update age, you must copy the rest!
setUser({ ...user, age: 31 });
```
The spread operator `...` is essential here.

# Forms & Inputs ğŸ“

In HTML, inputs manage their own state. In React, we want React to control it.

```jsx
const [val, setVal] = useState("");

<input 
  value={val} 
  onChange={e => setVal(e.target.value)} 
/>
```
The input's value is now driven by React state.

